##### Settings * toggle `Tri-state` checkbox to use `Next Cell` function, default is * : after running a cell, select next cell * : after running a cell, select next cell and try to scroll it to top * : after running a cell, do not select or move to next cell * `Switch`
to change interpreter, default is `eval5`. See [Code execution](#code-execution) below * click or or your browser icon, to remove selection * click or to lock/unlock notebook, when notebook is locked, cells can't be edited, run or removed * click or to toggle use of `typescript`, See [JavaScript vs TypeScript](#javascript-vs-typescript) below * click to show/hide table of content * click button to toggle light/dark color theme

input.source:
##### Markdown with LaTex

We use 

* [marked](https://github.com/markedjs/marked) to render [GitHub Flavored Markdown](https://github.github.com/gfm/)

* [katex](https://katex.org/) to render `LaTex`, example: $ c = \pm\sqrt{a^2 + b^2} $ (put latex inside `$$ ... $$ ` for display mode, `$ ... $` for inline mode); check out [Supported Functions](https://katex.org/docs/supported.html), [Support Table](https://katex.org/docs/support_table.html)

More Markdown tutorial can be found [here](/notebook/#markdown/tutorial.json)

More Latex tutorial can be found [here](/notebook/#latex/tutorial.json)

output.content:
Markdown with LaTex

We use

  • marked to render GitHub Flavored Markdown

  • katex to render LaTex, example: c=±a2+b2 c = \pm\sqrt{a^2 + b^2} c=±a2+b2​ (put latex inside $$ ... $$ for display mode, $ ... $ for inline mode); check out Supported Functions, Support Table

More Markdown tutorial can be found here

More Latex tutorial can be found here

LaTex protection

LaTeX content may contain text that could be interpreted as Markdown, e.g., $ {a}_{1} {a}_{2} $

Those are protected and rendered as LaTeX a1a2 {a}_{1} {a}_{2} a1​a2​ instead of Markdown {a}{1} {a}{2}

input.source:
##### Code Execution

Code is executed in an `iframe sandbox`, by one of below engines, based on `Switch` setting:

* [eval5](https://github.com/bplok20010/eval5), a js interperter implemented in js, this is the default engine. it runs javascript in a seperate `context`
* `eval is evil`, but there're situations when performance is too slow using a js interperter, like Monte Carlo Simulation. Using `eval` directly can speed things up, e.g. [Discrete Hedging](#quantlib/discretehedging.json), you may run with both engines and see the performance difference.

**Warning**: it's risky to use `eval`, only use it when it's abusolutely necessary

input.source: ##### JavaScript vs TypeScript If setting is on, code will be transpile by `typescript` (target=ES5) first, then feed to interperter. * In most cases, `ES5` javascript code should be enough, you may loose `var` to run in `un-restricted` mode, please refer to below example * Use `typescript` when you need `OOP` features like `inheritance`, or `ES6+` features, e.g. [Discrete Hedging](#quantlib/discretehedging.json)

output.content:
JavaScript vs TypeScript

If setting is on, code will be transpile by typescript (target=ES5) first, then feed to interperter.

  • In most cases, ES5 javascript code should be enough, you may loose var to run in un-restricted mode, please refer to below example
  • Use typescript when you need OOP features like inheritance, or ES6+ features, e.g. Discrete Hedging

input.source:
##### Render API
* last evaluated expression goes to cell output
  * object will be displayed as \[object, object\]
  * we're planning to add more smart rendering features, so you don't need to call render api direclty
* use `print()` for primitive data type, like `number` or `string`
  * it can be called multiple times in a cell, results are appended to cell output
* use `table()` for tabular data
  * only Array of objects are supported
  * objects need to have same properties
  * uses bootstrap table class, which fills entire cell output
  * it can be called multiple times in a cell, but this might change in the future
* use `plot()` to render chart. we use [highcharts](https://www.highcharts.com) library, chart is svg format
  * svg chart will take entire cell output
  * multiple plots in a cell is not supported
  * do not use `plot` with other render API

input.source:
##### Plot
 
* plot can be saved in and loaded from notebook as svg element
* when notebook is loaded, plot is `disconnected` from it's `data`, interactivity is lost, you have to re-run the cells that produce the `data`, and plot again
* when theme is changed, you have to re-run plot cell to reflect the color theme change

input.source:
##### The Option
Building the option requires only specification of its contract. Market data will be selected and processed later, depending on the calcuation methods.

output.content:
The Option

Building the option requires only specification of its contract. Market data will be selected and processed later, depending on the calcuation methods.

input.source:
option = new EuropeanOption(
  new PlainVanillaPayoff(Option.Type.Call, 100.0),
  new EuropeanExercise(DateExt.UTC('7,June,2014'))
)

output.content: [object Object]

input.source:
##### Black-Scholes
The different pricing methods are implemented as pricing engines holding the required market data. Quoted market data. We'll assume flat risk-free rate and volatility.

output.content:
Black-Scholes

The different pricing methods are implemented as pricing engines holding the required market data. Quoted market data. We'll assume flat risk-free rate and volatility.

input.source: u = new SimpleQuote(100.0);

output.content: [object Object]

input.source: r = new SimpleQuote(0.01);

output.content: [object Object]

input.source: sigma = new SimpleQuote(0.2);

output.content: [object Object]

input.source: The market data are encapsulated in a process object.

output.content: The market data are encapsulated in a process object.

input.source: riskFreeCurve = new FlatForward().ffInit3(0, new TARGET(), new Handle(r), new Actual360())

output.content: [object Object]

input.source: volatility = new BlackConstantVol().bcvInit4(0, new TARGET(), new Handle(sigma), new Actual360())

output.content: [object Object]

input.source:
process = new BlackScholesProcess(
  new Handle(u),
  new Handle(riskFreeCurve),
  new Handle(volatility)
)

output.content: [object Object]

input.source: Finally, the process is used to build the engine.

output.content: Finally, the process is used to build the engine.

input.source: engine = new AnalyticEuropeanEngine().init1(process)

output.content: [object Object]

input.source: option.setPricingEngine(engine)

output.content: undefined

input.source: npv = option.NPV()
